Key to Flags & Risk Calculations

Academic Risk (0–10)

Important: Only the single highest rule applies.
Students never receive multiple grade-gap penalties.
The model chooses the strongest one.
  • Below Target: GAP < 0 → +2
  • Serious Gap: GAP ≤ –1.5 → +3
  • High Grade Risk:
    • GAP ≤ –1 → +3
    • PP + below target → +3
    • SEN + below target → +3

Attendance Penalties (only if below target)

  • 80–89% → +2
  • <80% → +3

Behaviour Levels

  • B+3 (High):
    • 2+ BC removals (14d)
    • 6+ cautions (14d)
    • 2+ phone confiscations (28d)
    • Corridor ≠ High
  • B+2 (Med):
    • 3–5 cautions (14d)
    • 10–14 corridor events (28d)
  • B+1 (Low): At least one incident.
  • B+0: No incidents recorded.

Behaviour → Risk

  • Behaviour adds 0.5 per level
  • B+2 → +1.0 • B+3 → +1.5

Final Calculation

Final Risk = Academic + Behaviour
Example: 1.7 + (B+2 → +1.0) = 2.7

Flags

  • PP – Pupil Premium
  • SEN – Special Educational Needs
  • EAL – English as Additional Language
  • PA – Persistent Absence (<90%)
Prompted questions for SLT / Heads of Year
  • Which high-risk students need an immediate multi-agency discussion (HoY, SENCO, attendance, safeguarding)?
  • Are there PP or SEN students in the grid whose current support plans need revisiting?
  • Which 10–15 students should be the focus of a weekly review cycle between now and the next data drop?

Automatically generated summary of key priorities, designed to remove the need for separate narrative reports.

Curriculum & Faculty Priorities

  • BTEC Business: currently the weakest by mean GAP (vs Target) (-1.56). Review curriculum sequencing, targeted intervention and staffing.
  • Music Technology: strongest positive GAP (vs Target) (0.40). Capture and share "what works" practice across the faculty.
  • Severe underperformance: 29.2% of students have at least one subject ≥2 grades below target. Prioritise this group in subject and revision planning.
  • Use subject risk bands (High/Med/Low based on mean risk) to agree a short list of priority departments for SLT link monitoring.

Attendance & Pastoral Priorities

  • PA cohort: 19.8% of students have <90% attendance. Many are also high/medium academic risk.
  • High-risk students: 37 students in the high-risk band (risk ≥ 4.1). Agree weekly reviews and personalised plans (attendance, classroom support, revision).
  • Target the 92–95.9% attendance band early: students in this group show increasing below-target rates and risk escalation if attendance drifts.

7. Appendix & Glossary Reference

Key definitions
  • Risk Index (0–10): Internal composite score derived from subject-level risk flags and attendance. High risk ≥4.1, medium 2.2–4.0, low 0–2.1.
  • High-Risk Students (%): Percentage of students whose average risk index falls in the high band (≥4.1).
  • Students On/Above Target (%): Percentage of students with the majority of their entries at or above target (student-level view).
  • Subject Entries On/Above Target (%): Percentage of individual subject entries at or above target (entry-level view).
  • Below Target: Any subject where current grade is below the subject target; “severe” typically when ≥2 grades below.
  • PA (Persistent Absence): Typically attendance below 90% in the year to date.
  • SA (Severe Absence): Very low attendance (e.g. <50%) in the year to date.
  • Data Drops: Sequential data collections (e.g. Y10 T1–T3, Y11 T1) imported via SISRA and stored in Supabase.
